And the government is
collecting that $2 per pound

00:04:24.750 --> 00:04:26.260
on the imports.

00:04:26.260 --> 00:04:30.110
So in this situation, this
is the domestic supply.

00:04:30.110 --> 00:04:31.480
We've already talked about that.

00:04:31.480 --> 00:04:34.380
And so this amount right
over here, are the imports.

00:04:34.380 --> 00:04:36.130
So if you multiply this amount,

00:04:36.130 --> 00:04:39.310
which went from six million
pounds to 10 million pounds,

00:04:39.310 --> 00:04:42.170
so this is going to be
four million pounds,

00:04:42.170 --> 00:04:43.950
times the tariff,

00:04:43.950 --> 00:04:47.200
which is $2 per pound,

00:04:47.200 --> 00:04:49.290
per pound,

00:04:49.290 --> 00:04:51.140
you're going to get this area,

00:04:51.140 --> 00:04:53.450
which would be the government revenue.

00:04:53.450 --> 00:04:58.410
So this is going to be four million pounds

00:04:58.410 --> 00:05:01.230
times $2 per pound,

00:05:01.230 --> 00:05:04.360
times $2 per pound.

00:05:04.360 --> 00:05:05.960
Pound cancels out,

00:05:05.960 --> 00:05:08.120
and this is an area of a rectangle here.

00:05:08.120 --> 00:05:12.187
And so this is going to
be equal to eight million,

00:05:12.187 --> 00:05:13.263
$8 million.

00:05:14.160 --> 00:05:16.083
All right, now let's do part c.

00:05:17.120 --> 00:05:21.230
Given the world price of
$2, what per-unit tariff

00:05:21.230 --> 00:05:26.230
maximizes the sum of Loriland's
domestic consumer surplus

00:05:26.730 --> 00:05:29.170
and producer surplus?

00:05:29.170 --> 00:05:30.460
Pause the video once more,

00:05:30.460 --> 00:05:32.210
and see if you can figure this out.

00:05:33.340 --> 00:05:35.820
All right, so you might be tempted

00:05:35.820 --> 00:05:37.930
to try out a bunch of tariffs

00:05:37.930 --> 00:05:41.430
and figure out if you can
get a higher total surplus,

00:05:41.430 --> 00:05:44.040
but the important thing
to realize is any tariff

00:05:44.040 --> 00:05:47.540
is going to reduce your
total economic surplus.

00:05:47.540 --> 00:05:50.540
So you can immediately
go and say that, hey,

00:05:50.540 --> 00:05:53.380
the ideal per-unit tariff

00:05:53.380 --> 00:05:57.630
is going to be $0 per unit.

00:05:57.630 --> 00:05:59.950
And if you want to see
visually why that is,

00:05:59.950 --> 00:06:01.780
we talk about it in other videos.

00:06:01.780 --> 00:06:03.640
Remember, in the first situation,

00:06:03.640 --> 00:06:06.050
where we're just at the world
price without any tariffs,

00:06:06.050 --> 00:06:08.130
the total economic surplus,

00:06:08.130 --> 00:06:10.360
this is the domestic producer surplus,

00:06:10.360 --> 00:06:13.940
which isn't that much, but you
have a huge consumer surplus.

00:06:13.940 --> 00:06:16.603
You have all of this area as well.

00:06:17.620 --> 00:06:21.000
So those two triangles make
the total economic surplus.

00:06:21.000 --> 00:06:25.110
Now, a tariff is going
to raise this level.

00:06:25.110 --> 00:06:26.590
And as you raise this level,

00:06:26.590 --> 00:06:28.780
as you saw in the case of part b,

00:06:28.780 --> 00:06:31.570
well, you're going to
shrink this upper triangle.

00:06:31.570 --> 00:06:34.240
You will grow this bottom triangle,

00:06:34.240 --> 00:06:36.160
but you're still going to be smaller

00:06:36.160 --> 00:06:38.800
than your two triangles
that you had before.

00:06:38.800 --> 00:06:40.410
Because look at that second scenario,

00:06:40.410 --> 00:06:41.980
the scenario in part b.

00:06:41.980 --> 00:06:45.080
Your consumer surplus has now shrunk

00:06:45.080 --> 00:06:46.610
to this right over here.

00:06:46.610 --> 00:06:49.880
Your producer surplus has
